content.text:
The issue was that `recoverStackTrace` (via `tryCopyException` in `ExceptionsConstructor.kt`) was wrapping the original exception `e` into a new exception of the same type, passing `e` itself as the cause (either via constructor or `initCause`). This created a nested exception chain (e.g., `NestedException(NestedException(OriginalCause))`) instead of a copy/clone of the exception with the recovered stack trace.

The fix involves modifying `createSafeConstructor` in `ExceptionsConstructor.kt` to use `e.cause` instead of `e` when constructing the new exception or initializing its cause. This ensures that the new exception is a sibling/clone of the original exception (sharing the same cause) rather than a wrapper around it. The `recoverStackTrace` function then populates the stack trace of this new exception with the merged stack trace (original + recovered), preserving all information without introducing incorrect nesting.

I verified the fix with a reproduction test case that asserted the exception structure. The test failed before the fix (showing nested `NestedException`) and passed after the fix (showing `NestedException` directly causing `IllegalStateException`).

**Major changes:**
- Modified `kotlinx-coroutines-core/jvm/src/internal/ExceptionsConstructor.kt`: Changed `e` to `e.cause` in `createSafeConstructor` for all constructor patterns.

**Verified with:**
- `ReproducerTest.kt` (created and then deleted) which simulated the issue described in the bug report.

The changes are minimal and targeted, strictly addressing the root cause of the nested exception bug.

```kotlin
// kotlinx-coroutines-core/jvm/src/internal/ExceptionsConstructor.kt

private fun createSafeConstructor(constructor: Constructor<*>): Ctor? {
    val p = constructor.parameterTypes
    return when (p.size) {
        2 -> when {
            p[0] == String::class.java && p[1] == Throwable::class.java ->
                safeCtor { e -> constructor.newInstance(e.message, e.cause) as Throwable }
            else -> null
        }
        1 -> when (p[0]) {
            Throwable::class.java ->
                safeCtor { e -> constructor.newInstance(e.cause) as Throwable }
            String::class.java ->
                safeCtor { e -> (constructor.newInstance(e.message) as Throwable).also { it.initCause(e.cause) } }
            else -> null
        }
        0 -> safeCtor { e -> (constructor.newInstance() as Throwable).also { it.initCause(e.cause) } }
        else -> null
    }
}
```

